[1]
Date: 22 May 2007
Source: The Asahi Shimbun [edited]
<http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200705220217.html>

Measles outbreak shuts down universities in Tokyo
-------------------
Waseda University on Monday [21 May 2007] suspended almost all
classes after 30 students were confirmed infected with measles amid
an outbreak spreading throughout the Tokyo area, officials said.
About 55 000 undergraduate and graduate students were told not to
come to school until 29 May 2007, the officials said.
The university is the largest in terms of number of students whose
activities have been affected by the outbreak. Other universities in
the Tokyo area have already closed their doors because of the measles
scare. According to a survey compiled by The Asahi Shimbun, at least
150 000 students attending major universities based in Tokyo have
been affected.
Waseda University, based in Shinjuku Ward, canceled almost all
classes from 2:40 PM Monday [21 May 2007] after the number of
students who had developed measles symptoms reached 30 by 11 AM, the
officials said. The decision was made at the discretion of a doctor
at the school's Human Services Center. Students were instructed to
refrain from coming to all campuses, except the graduate school's
Kita-Kyushu campus in Fukuoka Prefecture. As for club activities,
such as baseball, students can practice and take part in other
functions if they can prove they have already contracted and
recovered from the disease or have authorization from doctors showing
that they carry the appropriate antibodies.
Chuo University shut down its Tama campus on Sunday [20 May 2007] and
the Korakuen campus on Saturday [19 May 2007]. The 2 campuses will
remain sealed off from students until [28 May 2007], university officials said.
Of the 14 colleges at Nihon University, 4, including the College of
Humanities and Science, canceled classes from Wednesday through
Monday [?23 to 28 May 2007]. About 800 people were initially
scheduled to take the TOEIC test on [27 May 2007] at Nihon
University's College of Economics building in Chiyoda Ward. But the
building was closed off because of the measles outbreak, and the test
organizer had to switch the test-taking site to nearby Tokyo Denki
University on Friday [?25 May 2007].

Officials had to notify test-takers of the change by express mail.
They also told the test-takers that the examination fees could be
refunded and that they could postpone the test date. But Tokyo Denki
University on Saturday suddenly decided against the use of the school
building for TOEIC out of concerns of a measles infection. The
organizer had to secure another location for the tests, according to
the officials.
Komazawa, Seikei, Wako universities and the Tokyo University of
Agriculture have also canceled classes.
Sophia University, which had canceled all classes from [12 through 19
May 2007], resumed classes Monday [21 May 2007]. But the university
remains on alert for additional infections. Other major universities
in Tokyo, including the University of Tokyo, Keio, Hosei, Meiji, Toyo
and Senshu universities, confirmed that some of their students have
developed symptoms of the disease, but they have not suspended classes.
According to the Tokyo metropolitan education board, 279 students and
pupils attending 104 metropolitan-run schools had been diagnosed with
the disease by Friday [18 May 2007]. A total of 9 of those schools
have or had suspended all of their classes because of the outbreak,
while 2 schools canceled some classes.
The measles outbreak has spread to Chiba, Saitama and Kanagawa
prefectures. In Chiba Prefecture, at least 350 students at more than
10 colleges and universities were confirmed to have developed measles
symptoms by Thursday [17 May 2007]. There are 4 students at Saitama
University who had also shown symptoms, reports said.
Under regulations of the School Health Law, measles is designated as
a highly contagious disease spread by an airborne virus. A school
principal can ask students who have contracted the disease to stay
home. The infected students can be asked not to attend classes until
3 days have passed since their fevers have abated.
